[vc_row][vc_column][vc_row_inner][vc_column_inner][vc_column_text]Ok in the last
lesson we learnt how to declare and assign values to various primitive types.
Let’s now look at some more operations this time using the intprimitive
type.[/vc_column_text][us_separator size=”small” show_line=”1″
icon=”fas|code”][us_iconbox icon=”fas|code” size=”48px” iconpos=”left”
title=”Downloads” alignment=”left”]To get started you can use the basic starter
project [/content/images/wordpress/2016/01/StarterProject.zip] and follow the
steps to compile the code examples for the lesson.[/us_iconbox][us_separator
size=”small” show_line=”1″
icon=”fas|code”][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][vc_row_inner][vc_column_inner][vc_column_text]
Setup
 1. Create a new package called:com.codenerve.beginner.lesson3
 2. Create a new class file called:BasicOperators.java with a main method

If you need help with this, please go back and look at the previous lessons
[https://www.codenerve.com/beginner-java/lesson-2-primitive-types/]

Adding
Within the main method of your class add the following lines of code:

int a = 10, b = 2;

You’ll notice I’ve done a few things different here.

Firstly, I’ve created two variables of type int on the one line, called a and b 
and assigned values to them. Thisone line syntaxis simply a handy shorthand for
creating and assigning my variables. You could also create these one two lines
as seen before in the previous lesson.

Secondly, you should also notice that I have decided to set up these variables
inside the main method. Doing this means they are local variables, not fields.
Which means they are only available inside the main method and not to other
methods. For the purposes of this lesson, this is fine.

Next, add the following code:

int result = a + b;
System.out.println("Result = " + result);

This is the simple add (+) operator which guess what adds two int’s together.
Lastly, we use the System class which Java provides for us to print the output.

You can run the code at each stage in this lesson to view the results of each
operator.

Subtracting
int result2 = a - b;
System.out.println("Result = " + result2);

Multiplication
int result3 = a * b;
System.out.println("Result = " + result3);

Division
int result4 = a / b;
System.out.println("Result = " + result4);

Modulus
int result5 = a % b;
System.out.println("Result = " + result5);

Increment
a++;
System.out.println("Result = " + a);

The ++ operation will add 1 to the current value of int a. This is useful for
keeping a count.

Decrement
a--;
System.out.println("Result = " + a);

The — operation will subtract 1 to the current value ofinta.  This is helpful
for maintaining a countdown.

Some more slightly complex calculations
int result6 = (a*b) * (a/b);
System.out.println("Result = " + result6);

int result7 = (a*b) * ( a * (a/b));
System.out.println("Result = " + result7);

int result8 = (a*b)/(a/b);
System.out.println("Result = " + result8);

int result9 = a * b * a / b;
System.out.println("Result = " + result9);


[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][us_separator size=”small”
show_line=”1″
icon=”fas|code”][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column][vc_column_text]Watch
out!
Dividing a primitive by zero causes the program to exit with a nasty error:

int result10 = (a*b) / 0;
System.out.println("Division by zero = " + result10);

Have a look at the exception:

Exception in thread “main” java.lang.ArithmeticException: / by zero

at com.codenerve.beginner.lesson3.BasicOperators.main(BasicOperators.java:63)

Ok, now that we’ve learnt how to use ints the next lesson will focus on
Strings.[/vc_column_text][us_separator size=”small” show_line=”1″
icon=”fas|code”][vc_column_text]

Next: Strings [https://www.codenerve.com/beginner-java/lesson-4-strings/]
[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column][us_post_navigation
layout=”sided”][/vc_column][/vc_row]

