[vc_row][vc_column][vc_row_inner][vc_column_inner][vc_column_text]Ok, In the
last few lessons we learn’t how to use Conditional statements and loops which we
are going to build upon in this lesson. However, so far in the lesson series we
have used the basic primitive types
[https://www.codenerve.com/beginner-java/lesson-2-primitive-types/]and Strings
[https://www.codenerve.com/beginner-java/lesson-4-strings/]to hold data for
us. In this lesson its time to cover a new data type called an Array.
[/vc_column_text][us_separator size=”small” show_line=”1″
icon=”fas|code”][us_iconbox icon=”fas|code” size=”48px” iconpos=”left”
title=”Downloads” alignment=”left”]To get started you can use the basic starter
project [/content/images/wordpress/2016/01/StarterProject.zip] and follow the
steps to compile the code examples for the lesson.[/us_iconbox][us_separator
show_line=”1″ icon=”fas|code”][vc_column_text]What are Arrays?
An array is a container that holds a number of values of a particular type.
Imagine we had to declare a number of book titles for example. With the
variables you’ve been taught in previous lessons we could write:

        String title1 = "a";
        String title2 = "b";
        String title3 = "c";
        String title4 = "d";

This isn’t a bad solution if there are only 2 or 3 books but what if there’s ten
or a hundred book’s? For this we are better using an array that can hold large
numbers of related data.[/vc_column_text][us_separator show_line=”1″
icon=”fas|code”][vc_column_text]

Creating Arrays
Ok so let’s create one! First off let’s create a new class called
Arrays.[/vc_column_text][vc_column_text]To create an array we use the following
syntax:

String[] books = {"1984", "Hitchhikers Guide to the galaxy", "Harry Potter", "A tale of two cities"};

Here we have an array of four elements. The elements are of type String, there
values are our book titles. To find out the length of an array we can use the
.length variable contained inside an array object. For example:

System.out.println("There are " + books.length + " books in the array");

Will output:

"There are 4 books in the array"

[/vc_column_text][us_separator show_line=”1″ icon=”fas|code”][vc_column_text]
Accessing elements in Arrays
To access one of our titles we can use the elements numerical index. But first
let me explain this a little more. To help do this I’m going to visualise the
array we created above:


[https://www.ni-geeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/Screen-Shot-2014-09-23-at-18.34.17.png]















An array consists of a number of elements. The number of elements depends on the
number of values you inserted when you created the array. You should note that
the first elements index is zero. So to access the first element in the array we
would use:

books[0]

Try it! Create our array above and use the following to print out the
second element in the array:

System.out.println("Our second title is: " + books[1]);

[/vc_column_text][us_separator show_line=”1″ icon=”fas|code”][vc_column_text]
Iterating through Arrays
So now you’re able to extract values from the array which is great. But now were
going to combine our knowledge of arrays with an older lesson on loops
[https://www.codenerve.com/beginner-java/lesson-6-loops/]. Iterating through an
array is a very common pattern in programming and will be a very powerful tool
to have. Lets look at the following code:

    private static void iteratingThroughAnArray() {

        String[] books = {"1984", "Hitchhikers Guide to the galaxy", "Harry Potter", "A tale of two cities"};

        for (int i = 0; i < books.length; i++) {
            System.out.println("Book " + i + " Title: " + books[i]);
        }
    }

Add this method to your Arrays class and call it from your main method. You will
see in the console output it will loop through every element in the array you
created and print each title out.

Whats interesting here is the use of the loops i variable. As the for loop steps
through each loop, i is incremented. As you can see it starts at zero. Which is
perfect for accessing the first element in the array. We also set the upper
limit of the array to be < books.length. This is very important! I encourage you
to try to access an element in the array that doesn’t exist to see why! Try
books[99] for example (Hint: You will see lots of
red!).[/vc_column_text][us_separator show_line=”1″
icon=”fas|code”][vc_column_text]

Reminder of the Java 5 Enhanced For loop
So now were going to remind ourselves of the enhanced for loop. We briefly
covered this in the loops lesson
[https://www.codenerve.com/beginner-java/lesson-6-loops/]. Lets have a look at
another method which does the same thing as the previous example only using the
enhanced loop:

    private static void usingTheEnhancedForLoop() {

        String[] books = {"1984", "Hitchhikers Guide to the galaxy", "Harry Potter", "A tale of two cities"};

        for (String book : books) {
            System.out.println("Title: " + book);
        }

    }

You’ll see from the output this is (almost) the same method as before.
An advantage however is the i variable and the books.length are not required.
This is therefore less prone to errors (like the ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException
you would have seen if you’d tried to access an element that doesn’t exist).

It also has a few drawbacks. You cannot access the numerical index of the
current element in the array because there is no i variable and also these loops
can only go in one direction. In the previous loop you could have declared your
array like:

    private static void iteratingThroughAnArray_backwards() {

        String[] books = {"1984", "Hitchhikers Guide to the galaxy", "Harry Potter", "A tale of two cities"};

        for (int i = books.length -1; i >= 0; i--) {
            System.out.println("Book " + i + " Title: " + books[i]);
        }
    }

This array will print the titles in the reverse order. This is why its useful to
learn both arrays depending on what you need to do with your
array.[/vc_column_text][us_separator show_line=”1″
icon=”fas|code”][vc_column_text]

Arrays With Methods
As with all the other types you have learnt, arrays can be passed into and
returned from methods.

Passing in arrays:

    private static void usingArraysInMethods(String[] anotherStringArray) {
        // arrays like other data types can be passed into methods and used

        for (String book : anotherStringArray) {
            System.out.println("Title: " + book);
        }
    }

Passing in and returning arrays:

    private static String[] returningArraysFromMethods(String[] anotherStringArray) {

        // arrays like other data types can be passed into methods and also returned

        for (String book : anotherStringArray) {
            // lets make all items in the array lower case
            book = book.toLowerCase();

            System.out.println("Title: " + book);
        }
        return anotherStringArray;
    }

The example above takes in the array makes all values lower case and returns the
array.[/vc_column_text][us_separator show_line=”1″
icon=”fas|code”][vc_column_text]

2D Arrays
Are last example in the lesson is the Two Dimensional array. So far in this
lesson we have just been using strings but you can use any type. We could create
arrays of type int, boolean OR another array!

The easiest way to think of a 2D array is an array of arrays. Lets have a look
at creating one:

    private static void AnotherTwoDimensionalArray() {
        String[][] books = {
                {"1984", "George Orwell", "£9.99"},
                {"Hitchhikers Guide to the galaxy", "Douglas Adams", "£9.99"}};

        for (int i = 0; i < books.length; i++) {

            System.out.println("Title: " + books[i][0] + " Author: " + books[i][1] + " Price: " + books[i][2]);
        }
    }

Creating the array you will see we use two groups of square brackets instead of
one to declare a 2d array:

String[][] books

You will also see that when adding our values to the 2d array there are arrays
inside of the main array:

{
    {"1984", "George Orwell", "£9.99"},
    {"Hitchhikers Guide to the galaxy", "Douglas Adams", "£9.99"}
};

Accessing values in the array is also different. We again need to use two square
brackets with two numerical indexes:

books[x][y]

To explain this lets use another diagram:


[https://www.ni-geeks.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/Screen-Shot-2014-09-23-at-21.55.36.png]

As mentioned we can access a 2d with a two numerical indexes x and y in this
case. The diagram shows the x index accessing the first element in the outside
array and the y accessing an element in the array that is referred to by x.

Surprisingly the java spec limits the amount of dimensions you can create on an
array to 255! I have yet to need anything beyond 3 and I can only imagine that
to require a 255d array you would need to be a physics genius!

As always try to get the code running and play around with it. See if you can
iterate through the 2d array above and access the elements within
it.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][vc_row_inner][vc_column_inner][us_separator
show_line=”1″ icon=”fas|code”][vc_column_text]

Next: Reading Console Input
[https://www.codenerve.com/beginner-java/lesson-9-reading-console-input/]
[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column][us_post_navigation
