<li>A brief history of streams API</li>
<li>Types of operations Aggregate/intermediate / terminal</li>
</ul>
[/vc_column_text][us_separator show_line=&#8221;1&#8243; icon=&#8221;fas|code&#8221;][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_column][/vc_column][vc_row][vc_column][us_cta title=&#8221;Sample Code&#8221; color=&#8221;secondary&#8221; btn_label=&#8221;Code&#8221; btn_link=&#8221;url:https%3A%2F%2Fgithub.com%2Fcodenerve-com%2Ftutorials%2Ftree%2Fmaster%2Fjava-cookbook||target:%20_blank|&#8221; btn_style=&#8221;2&#8243; btn_size=&#8221;15px&#8221; btn_icon=&#8221;fab|github&#8221;]The code for this lesson is available on GitHub[/us_cta][us_separator show_line=&#8221;1&#8243; icon=&#8221;fas|code&#8221;][vc_column_text]
<h2>Basic operations on Lists</h2>
[/vc_column_text][us_separator size=&#8221;small&#8221; show_line=&#8221;1&#8243; icon=&#8221;fas|code&#8221;][vc_tta_tour switch_sections=&#8221;hover&#8221; layout=&#8221;trendy&#8221; title_font=&#8221;&#8221;][vc_tta_section icon=&#8221;fas|sort&#8221; tab_id=&#8221;1593167147786-cbc0cd2f-dca3&#8243; title=&#8221;Sort&#8221;][vc_column_text]
<h3>Input data</h3>
<p>The following examples will use a list of book titles (strings):</p>
<p><span style="color: #666d70;">(These have been taken at random from <a style="color: #666d70;" href="https://devconnected.com/the-10-best-software-engineering-books-in-2019/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">devconnected.com&#8217;s best Software Engineering Books in 2019</a>)</span></p>
<pre class="lang:java decode:true">    private final List&lt;String&gt; books = asList(
            "Clean Code",
            "Design Patterns: Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented Software",
            "Patterns of Enterprise Application Architecture",
            "Enterprise Integration Patterns",
            "The Mythical Man-Month",
            "Code Complete",
            "Git for Teams",
            "Refactoring: Improving the Design of Existing Code",
            "The Art of Unit Testing",
            "Soft Skills: The Software Developer’s Life Manual");
</pre>
[/vc_column_text][us_separator size=&#8221;small&#8221;][vc_column_text]
<h4>Sort strings in alphabetical order</h4>
<p>Sorting a list of books in alphabetical order using <em>sorted(</em>) i.e. <a href="https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/collections/interfaces/order.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">natural ordering</a>:</p>
<pre class="lang:java decode:true ">    @Test
    void sort_alphabetical() {
        List&lt;Object&gt; sortedList =
                books.stream()
                        .sorted()
                        .collect(toList());

        assertThat(sortedList.get(0), is(equalTo("Clean Code")));
        assertThat(sortedList.get(sortedList.size() -1), is(equalTo("The Mythical Man-Month")));
    }</pre>
[/vc_column_text][us_separator size=&#8221;small&#8221;][vc_column_text]
<h4>Sort strings in reverse alphabetical order</h4>
<p>Sorting a list of books in reverse alphabetical order using <em>sorted(Comparator.reverseOrder())</em>:</p>
<pre class="lang:java decode:true ">    @Test
    void sort_reverse_alphabetical() {
        List&lt;Object&gt; sortedList =
                books.stream()
                        .sorted(Comparator.reverseOrder())
                        .collect(toList());

        assertThat(sortedList.get(0), is(equalTo("The Mythical Man-Month")));
        assertThat(sortedList.get(sortedList.size() -1), is(equalTo("Clean Code")));
    }</pre>
[/vc_column_text][us_separator size=&#8221;small&#8221;][vc_column_text]
<h4>Sort by string length</h4>
<p>Sort the books in order of there title length using <em>sorted(Comparator.comparing(String::length)):</em></p>
<pre class="lang:java decode:true ">    @Test
    void sort_by_title_length() {
        List&lt;Object&gt; sortedList =
                books.stream()
                        .sorted(Comparator.comparing(String::length))
                        .collect(toList());

        assertThat(sortedList.get(0), is(equalTo("Clean Code"))); // the shortest title
        assertThat(sortedList.get(sortedList.size() -1), is(equalTo("Design Patterns: Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented Software"))); // the longest title
    }</pre>
[/vc_column_text][us_separator size=&#8221;small&#8221;][vc_column_text]
<h4>Sort string using a custom comparator</h4>
<p>Sort the number of books by the number of times a letter &#8216;e&#8217; occurs in there title:</p>
<pre class="lang:java decode:true ">    @Test
    void sort_by_custom_comparator() {
        List&lt;Object&gt; sortedList =
                books.stream()
                        .sorted(new CustomComparator())
                        .collect(toList());

        // the letter 3 occurs the most in this book.
        assertThat(sortedList.get(0), is(equalTo("Design Patterns: Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented Software")));
    }</pre>
<p>Where the custom comparator is:</p>
<pre class="lang:java decode:true ">import java.util.Comparator;

public class CustomComparator implements Comparator&lt;String&gt; {

    /*
        Sorts by the number of occurrences of the character 'e' in any given string
     */
    @Override
    public int compare(String string, String string2) {
        long stringCount = string.chars().filter(ch -&gt; ch == 'e').count();
        long secondStringCount = string2.chars().filter(ch -&gt; ch == 'e').count();
        return Long.compare(secondStringCount, stringCount);
    }
}</pre>
[/vc_column_text][/vc_tta_section][vc_tta_section icon=&#8221;fas|filter&#8221; tab_id=&#8221;1593167147801-27a547cc-163a&#8221; title=&#8221;Filter&#8221;][vc_column_text]
<h3>Input data</h3>
<p>The following examples will use a list of book objects. Each book contains a title, an author and a rating out of 5:</p>
<p><span style="color: #666d70;">N.B. these are all 5-star books but I have changed the ratings for the purpose of these examples.</span></p>
<pre class="lang:java decode:true">    private final List&lt;Book&gt; books = asList(
            new Book("Clean Code", "Robert Martin", 5),
            new Book("Design Patterns: Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented Software", "Eric Gamma", 4),
            new Book("Patterns of Enterprise Application Architecture", "Martin Fowler", 3),
            new Book("Enterprise Integration Patterns", "Gregor Hohpe", 5),
            new Book("The Mythical Man-Month", "Frederick Brooks", 4),
            new Book("Code Complete", "Steve McConnell", 3),
            new Book("Git for Teams", "Emma Hogbin Westby", 5),
            new Book("Refactoring: Improving the Design of Existing Code", "Martin Fowler", 4),
            new Book("The Art of Unit Testing", "Roy Osherove", 3),
            new Book("Soft Skills: The Software Developer’s Life Manual", "John Sonmez", 5));
</pre>
[/vc_column_text][us_separator size=&#8221;small&#8221; show_line=&#8221;1&#8243; icon=&#8221;fas|code&#8221;][vc_column_text]
<h3>Basic Filter</h3>
<p>Filter Book objects based on there rating:</p>
<pre class="lang:java decode:true ">    @Test
    void filter_five_star_books() {

        List&lt;Book&gt; fiveStarBooks = books.stream()
                .filter(book -&gt; book.getRating() == 5)
                .collect(Collectors.toList());

        assertThat(fiveStarBooks.size(), is(equalTo(4)));
    }</pre>
[/vc_column_text][us_separator size=&#8221;small&#8221; show_line=&#8221;1&#8243; icon=&#8221;fas|code&#8221;][vc_column_text]
<h3>Multiple Filters</h3>
<p>Since filter(&#8230;) is an intermediate operation you can call as many as you like. This example finds all five-star books with &#8220;Git&#8221; in their title:</p>
<pre class="lang:java decode:true ">    @Test
    void filter_five_star_git_books() {
        List&lt;Book&gt; fiveStarGitBooks = books.stream()
                .filter(book -&gt; book.getRating() == 5)
                .filter(book -&gt; book.getTitle().contains("Git"))
                .collect(Collectors.toList());

        assertThat(fiveStarGitBooks.size(), is(equalTo(1)));
    }</pre>
[/vc_column_text][us_separator size=&#8221;small&#8221; show_line=&#8221;1&#8243; icon=&#8221;fas|code&#8221;][vc_column_text]
<h3>Expanding Lambda Body</h3>
<p>More complicated predicate conditions can be created by expanding out the filters lambda body. This filters all boos with an even rating:</p>
<pre class="lang:java decode:true ">    @Test
    void filter_even_ratings() {
        List&lt;Book&gt; bookILike = books.stream()
                .filter(book -&gt; {
                    return book.getRating() % 2 == 0;
                })
                .collect(Collectors.toList());

        assertThat(bookILike.size(), is(equalTo(3)));
    }</pre>
[/vc_column_text][us_separator size=&#8221;small&#8221; show_line=&#8221;1&#8243; icon=&#8221;fas|code&#8221;][vc_column_text]
<h3>Filtering on predicates</h3>
<p>Useful for code re-use you can declare Predicates elsewhere and use in your filters. This example finds all book titles with &#8220;Patterns&#8221; in the title:</p>
<pre class="lang:java decode:true ">    @Test
    void filter_pattern_books() {
        List&lt;Book&gt; fiveStarBooks = books.stream()
                .filter(patternBooks)
                .collect(Collectors.toList());

        assertThat(fiveStarBooks.size(), is(equalTo(3)));
    }</pre>
<p>In this case the predicate is a field:</p>
<pre class="lang:java decode:true ">private final Predicate&lt;Book&gt; patternBooks = book -&gt; book.getTitle().contains("Patterns");</pre>
[/vc_column_text][us_separator size=&#8221;small&#8221; show_line=&#8221;1&#8243; icon=&#8221;fas|code&#8221;][vc_column_text]
<h3>findAny</h3>
<p>Used to find any item in the collection that matches the filter(s) conditions. Returns an optional which could be empty (see <a href="https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/Optional.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">optionals</a> for more info). It is also important to note that this method is non-deterministic and can return different results if run multiple times.</p>
<p>This example finds any Robert Martin book:</p>
<pre class="lang:java decode:true ">    @Test
    void find_a_robert_martin_book() {
        Optional&lt;Book&gt; aRobertMartinBook = books.stream()
                .filter(book -&gt; book.getAuthor().contains("Martin Fowler"))
                .findAny();

        assertThat(aRobertMartinBook.get().getAuthor(), is(equalTo("Martin Fowler")));
    }</pre>
[/vc_column_text][us_separator size=&#8221;small&#8221; show_line=&#8221;1&#8243; icon=&#8221;fas|code&#8221;][vc_column_text]
<h3>orElse</h3>
<p>An alternative to returning an optional from a findAny() call is to use <em>orElse(&#8230;.). </em>This allows us to return a default value if there are no matches in the stream.</p>
<p>This example returns a Martin Fowler book if it exists in the collection or null if nothing is found:</p>
<pre class="lang:java decode:true ">    @Test
    void find_a_martin_fowler_book() {
        Book aMartinFowlerBook = books.stream()
                .filter(book -&gt; book.getAuthor().contains("Martin Fowler"))
                .findAny()
                .orElse(null);

        assertThat(aMartinFowlerBook.getAuthor(), is(equalTo("Martin Fowler")));
    }</pre>
